A single crew member aboard a spacecraft works a series of {{ round_count }} system anomalies, one at a time, with two Mission Control flight controllers over an air-to-ground comm loop. Every character sent on the comm loop costs one simulated second (fixed per-anomaly budget: {{ round_time_budget_seconds }}s). If total communication time exceeds the budget, the failing system is permanently lost.

The astronaut sees the physical panel — which unit's talkback tripped and the current switch and tie configuration — and is the only one who can operate controls. The Telemetry Officer reads the downlinked telemetry — the exact fault plus the required hold time and corrective setting. The Systems Engineer holds the malfunction-procedures handbook and the vehicle's current configuration table, which rotates each anomaly so that the procedure for a given fault changes with the configuration. No single pair can complete a procedure: the engineer's template needs the unit and configuration from the crew and the hold and setting from the Telemetry Officer, and only the crew can act.

Anomalies cascade: resolving one fault can reveal a secondary fault, which must be diagnosed and corrected in turn before the vehicle is fully stabilized.{% if postmortem_enabled %} After each anomaly, a debrief channel opens where the three can talk at no time cost.{% endif %}
